41 Sec. 6. (a) As used in this section, "serious adverse event" means
42 any negative medical occurrence associated with the use of a
ES 282—LS 7068/DI 104

7
1 prescription medication or treatment provided that results in,
2 based on a reasonable medical judgment, jeopardy to an
3 individual's health resulting in medical or surgical intervention or
4 any of the following outcomes:
5 (1) Death.
6 (2) A life threatening medical occurrence.
7 (3) Inpatient hospitalization or prolonging of an existing
8 hospitalization.
9 (b) A medical spa shall notify the board in the manner
10 prescribed by the board not later than fifteen (15) days after the
11 occurrence of a patient's serious adverse event. The notice must
12 include, to the extent that the information may be obtained or
13 reasonably available from the source, the following:
14 (1) The name of the patient, the prescription medication
15 treatment involved, and the date of the serious adverse event.
16 (2) The nature and location of the serious adverse event.
17 (3) The medical records for the patient concerning the serious
18 adverse event.
19 Sec. 7. The board may investigate a responsible practitioner
20 concerning any claim of a violation of this chapter and forward
21 any substantiated claim to the governing board of the responsible
22 practitioner.
23 Sec. 8. An individual licensed or certified under this title who
24 violates this chapter is subject to discipline under IC 25-1-9.
25 Sec. 9. A medical spa may not provide health care services and
26 cosmetic and lifestyle treatments to a consumer at a location other
27 than the medical spa office unless the health care service or
28 treatment is being performed in another location for educational
29 or training purposes of individuals who intend to provide these
30 services or treatment.
31 Sec. 10. (a) A medical spa shall comply with the advertising
32 requirements set forth in IC 25-1-10.3.
33 (b) The board may suspend a registration under this chapter for
34 a violation of IC 25-1-10.3.
35 Sec. 11. (a) The board shall consult with the appropriate
36 professional board that has oversight of a profession concerning
37 any issues concerning the practice of the profession as it relates to
38 providing services in a medical spa.
39 (b) Nothing in this chapter precludes a governing board of a
40 practitioner to take any action against a practitioner for a violation
41 of the practitioner's license or certification.
